Ecological range expansion may be a particularly important aspect of the invasion process to document because it can influence future invasion dynamics in two key ways. First, expansion into a broader range of ecological conditions may enhance a species' rate of spread by increasing connectivity among suitable habitats and the probability of dispersal to suitable sites (
 With 2002; 
 Hastings 
  et al. 2005
 ; 
 Theoharides and Dukes 2007). Second, if newly colonized habitats have greater resource availability than ancestral habitats (which is typical of the disturbed, open conditions colonized by many invasive species, 
 Theoharides and Dukes 2007), ecological range expansion may increase individual fitness, population growth rate and propagule pressure on adjacent habitats (
 Hastings 
  et al. 2005
 ; 
 Lockwood 
  et al. 2005
 ).
